{"primaryContentSections":[{"kind":"declarations","declarations":[{"tokens":[{"kind":"keyword","text":"case"},{"kind":"text","text":" "},{"kind":"identifier","text":"linkOnceODR"}],"languages":["swift"],"platforms":["macOS"]}]},{"kind":"content","content":[{"anchor":"discussion","level":2,"type":"heading","text":"Discussion"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Some languages allow differing globals to be merged, such as two functions with different"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"semantics. Other languages, such as C++, ensure that only equivalent globals are ever merged"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"(the “one definition rule” — “ODR”). Such languages can use the "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"linkonce_odr"},{"type":"text","text":" and "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"weak_odr"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"linkage types to indicate that the global will only be merged with equivalent globals. These"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"linkage types are otherwise the same as their non-odr versions."}]}]}],"schemaVersion":{"major":0,"minor":3,"patch":0},"sections":[],"variants":[{"paths":["\/documentation\/llvm\/linkage\/linkonceodr"],"traits":[{"interfaceLanguage":"swift"}]}],"identifier":{"url":"doc:\/\/LLVM\/documentation\/LLVM\/Linkage\/linkOnceODR","interfaceLanguage":"swift"},"abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"The name is merged with other globals of the same name when linkage occurs."}],"kind":"symbol","metadata":{"fragments":[{"kind":"keyword","text":"case"},{"kind":"text","text":" "},{"kind":"identifier","text":"linkOnceODR"}],"title":"Linkage.linkOnceODR","roleHeading":"Case","role":"symbol","symbolKind":"case","externalID":"s:4LLVM7LinkageO11linkOnceODRyA2CmF","modules":[{"name":"LLVM"}]},"hierarchy":{"paths":[["doc:\/\/LLVM\/documentation\/LLVM","doc:\/\/LLVM\/documentation\/LLVM\/Linkage"]]},"references":{"doc://LLVM/documentation/LLVM/Linkage":{"role":"sy